{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/0028060169A/1938012801/0064.xml":{"full_text":"POTOMAC POWER\nNet for 1937 $440,667.96\nAbove 1936\u2014December\nIncome Also Higher.\nBy EDWARD C. STONE.\nReporting another year of steady\nand substantial business improve\nment. the Potomac Electric Power Co.\nannounced today that net income\nfor 1937 amounted to $4,886,973.93, a\ngain of $440,667.96 over 1936. Ac\ncording to the financial statement\nfiled with the Public Utilities Com\nmission. operating expenses were\nhigher than in 1936. but operating\nrevenues also advanced even more.\nOperating revenues totaled $14,\n725.380, an increase over 1936 of\n$631,390.58. or 4.48 per cent. At\nthe same time operating expenses\ncalled for $8,873,280.68, an increase\nof $273,086.59 over the previous year,\nor 3.18 per cent, leaving a net income\nfrom operations of $5,852,099.32, an\nincrease of $358,203.99. or 6.52 per\ncent.\nGross earnings amounted to $5,917,\n336.32, a gain of $285,838.61, or 5.8\nper cent. The usual deductions for\ninterest and other purposes required\n$1,030,362.86. which was lower than\nthe amount deducted in 1936 by $154,\n829.36. leaving the above-stated nota\nble increase in the power concern\u2019s\ntotal net income. While wages, fuel\nand other casts were heavier during\nthe year, there was a marked rise\nin the year's kilowatt hour sales.\nThe company also filed the Decem\nber report today, which disclosed op\nerating revenues of $1,295,060.38, up\n$51,997.33, or 4.18 per cent. Op\nerating expenses required $842,850.78.\nan increase over December. 1936. of\n$52,243.99, or 6.61 per cent. This\nleft net operating revenues of $452,\n209.60, off $246.66.\nAfter inclusion of all other income\nand deduction for bond interest and\ndividends, the power company had\na net income for December of $351,\n883.74. an increase of $27,906.14, or\n8.61 per cent over December. 1936.\nSavings Deposits Climh.\nThrift got a big boost in 1937, when\ndepositors in the Nation's mutual sav\nings banks added an aggregate sum of\n$113,786,770 to their accounts during\nthe year, the National Association of\nMutual Savings Banks reported today.\nDeposits on December 31 totaled $10,\n126,381.152. against $10,012,594,382 on\nthe same date in 1936.\nIn number of accounts, which sav\nings bank officials consider the real\nbarometer of thrift, the total rose to\n14,578.186 from 14,398.920 a year ago,\na gain of 179,266 accounts. The aver\nage of accounts was $694.63, compared\nto $695.30 the year before.\nAll of the year\u2019s totals were but\nslightly below the highest figures of\nmutual institutions. In the case of\ncombined surplus account the total\nrose to a new peak of $1,319,217,549\nfrom $1,260,319,338 on December 31,\n1936, an increase for the year of $58,\n898,211.\nAssets of all mutual savings institu\ntions, operating in 17 States, at the\nyear end amounted to $11,500,624,304,\ncompared to $11,357,442,351 a year\nego. a gain of $143,181,953.\nRestricted investment opportunities\nand low rate of earnings continued to\naffect the rate of dividends paid to de\npositors, which averaged from 2 to 2>2\nper cent,\nAmong the 100 largest mutual banks\nin the United States are the Savings\nBank of Baltimore, with over $93,\n000.000 in deposits, and the Eutaw\nSavings Bank, Baltimore, with $50,\n034,885 in deposits.\nBank Loans Reveal Decline.\nThe Federal Reserve Board's Jan\nuary Bulletin states that the volume\nof loans at reporting members\u2019 banks\nin 101 leading cities declined sharply\nIn the five weeks ending January 19,\nwhile their holdings of investments\nshowed little net change. Declines\noccurred in loans to security brokers\nand dealers and in commercial loans,\nwhich decreased both in New York\nCity and in other leading cities.\nInterbank balances were built up\nduring the period, while other deposits\ndecreased somewhat, reflecting largely\nthe repayment of bank loans, partly\noffset by a return flow of currency\nfrom circulation.\nExcess reserves of member banks\nIncreased in the four weeks ending\nJanuary 19 from $1,010,000,000 to\n$1,370,000,000 and were larger than at\nany time since May 1. The post\nholiday decline in money in circula\ntion. which accounted for this growth\nof excess reserves, was larger than\nthe increase that occurred before\nChristmas.\nOutlook Held Much Better.\n\u2018'The general business outlook Is\nmuch improved, particularly in those\nlines which will benefit from the ex\npenditures for national defense,\u201d ac\ncording to the monthly survey of the\ncondition of business in the February\nissue of the magazine \"Banking.\u201d offi\ncial publication of the American Bank\ners Association.\nThe country\u2019s great need at pres\nent,\u201d it continues, \"is an old-fashioned\nera of good feeling between business,\nlabor and Government, founded on\nreal understanding. If the present\ntruce is temporary its benefits will\nalso be temporary. Nothing of a per\nmanent nature in the direction of\nsound recovery will be accomplished\nIn an atmosphere of fault finding and\ndistrust.\u201d\n\"The White House conferences,\nbringing together representatives of\nthe Government, industry, finance and\nlabor, gave a fillip to returning con\nfidence,\u201d the publication declares.\nToday\u2019s Trading on Exchange.\nThe cold wave evidently hit trading\non the Washington Stock Exchange\ntoday, the only activity being in Po\ntomac Electric Power 6 pier cent pre\nferred stock at recent levels.\nAs noted elsewhere in today\u2019s finan\ncial section of The Star, the Capital\nTransit Co. filed the yearly report\nwith the Public Utilities Commission.\nThis showed an increase of $106,055.03\nin total net income over the previous\nyear.\nThe repiort also disclosed substan\ntial improvement in the. December\nearnings under the new fare rates.\nTransit stock was quiet on the ex\nchange with 8% bid and 10 asked.\nSTOCK EXCHANGE SEAT\nDECLINES TO $65,000\nNEW YORK, Jan. 28 (A>).\u2014The sale\nof a New York Stock Exchange seat\nwas arranged today at $65,000, a drop\nof $10,000 from the previous transfer\non January 12.\nOn the basis of today\u2019s sale seat\nvalues are only slightly above the 18\nyear low level, established last October,\nwith the transfer of a membership at\n$61,000. The high quotation for 1937\nwas (134,000 In January.\ni\nTRANSACTIONS ON THE NEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE\nBy Private Wire Direct te The Star.\n*2:30 p.m.\nPrev. 1037-8 Stock end Sales\u2014 Net\nHigh. Low. Dividend Rate. Add UO. High. Low. Close, chge.\n56 36 Abbott Lab (1.60a). 1 36% 3b% 36%-%\n85 42 Acme Steel (4) _ 1 41% 41% 41% W\n22% 7% Adams Exp (,60k).. 9 8% 8% v 8%\n28% 17% Adams-Millla <2a)_. 1 19% 19% 19%\n36 16% Addressog (1.40)_ 2 21% 21% 21%\n4% 1% Advance Rumley_. 1 1% 1% 1%\n80% 44% Air Reduction (la). 13 48 46% 46%-1%\n5% Air-Way El Appl... 8 1% 1 1%\n15% 8 Alaska Jun (.\u00ab0a)__ 83 12% 12 12 V*\n6% 1 Alleghany 2 1% 1% 1%\n.69% 11 Alleg pf $30 ww_ 2 12% 12 12%\n52% 10% Alleg prpf _ ,3 14 13% 14 -1\n45% 13 Allegheny Steel_ 14 16% 15% 15%-%\n27% 6% Allen Indus (1) _ 2 8 7% 7%\n258% 145 Allied Chem D 6a. 2 161 168 161 +1\n38% 10 Allied Mills (2e).._ 3 12 11% 11%-%\n21% 6% Allied Stores _ 15 7 6% 7\n83% 34 Atlls-Chaltnl3.50|r). 35 42 39% 42\n39% 8% Alpha Portland (1). 1 12 12 12\n8% 1% Amal Leather_ 2 2% 2% 2%\n114% 61% Amerada (2) 4 60% 60 60 -1\n41% 10 Am Bk Note (.25e). 5 13 12% 12%\n75% 49% Am Bank N pf (3).. 40b 52% 52% 52%+\n80% 28 Am Brake Sh 3.40g. 11 3.3 31 31% -1%\n121 69 Am Can (4) 7 78 75% 75% -1%\n71 15% Am Car A Ey (%|)_. 6 21% 20% 21%\n104% 36 Am Car F pf (4g). 1 40 40 40\n33% 11% Am Chain <1.50g)._. 11 14% 13% 13%-%\n112 90 Am Chicle (4a)_ 1 99% 99% 99'* -1%\n23% 6% Am Colortype 16 6 6\n3i>% 8% Am Cornel Alco ,50g 3 11% 11% 11%\n33% 12% Am Cryst Sug(.50e) 2 14% 14% 14%\n99% 78% Am Crys Sug pf (6) _ 30a 80 79 79 -1\n13% 2 Am Encaustic Til 7 4 3% 3%\n13% 2% Am Foreign Pow. 16 3% 3 3%\n68% 14% Am F P $6 pf 1 14 1