i\n65 19 Wheeling Steel 5 22V* 21'* 22'4 V*\n90*i 65 WheelStlprpf (5). 2 56V, 65 55 -4\n33 6 White Motor 18 10'i 9% 10V* Vi\n18*4 8l4 White Rk M Sp 1.40 1 10'* 10V* 10v*\n6*4 1*\u00bb White Sew Mach 1 2% 2% 2% Vi\nBV* 2 Wiilys-Overiand 3 2% 2V\u00bb 2Vi\n12 4** Willys-Over pf (.60) 4 6*4 5** 6*. *4\n12Vi 4V4 Wilson Co _ 30 4*\u00bb 4*. 44 1*\n91*4 49*4 Wilson pf (6) _ 2 51 6OV4 SOV4 -1%\n19vt 10% Woodward Iron Co. 7 14Vi 13** 14 1*\n65*\u00ab 34 Woolwortb (2.40)... 13 38*\u00bb 37V* 38 V*\n47 12 Worthington Pump. 8 15*4 15 lSVi *4\n54 35 Worth cv pr pf 4.50. 4 37 36 36 +1\n128 38 Wright Aero (2g)\u2014 160s 77*4 74 74 -1\n62V* 21*4 Yale Town# 60a\u2014 1 21 21 21 *4\n37% 71* Yellow Truck 70 13V* 12Vi 13\n142 68 Yellow Trk pf (7)-_ 10s 83 83 83 -3'4\n46V* 12V% Young Sprg Wire 5 1 574 1 5V4 15V4\n101T* 34V* Youngst S&T 3.25g. 65 36*4 34** 35Vt -1\n115 70 Yngstn S&T pf 5.50. 1 73'* 73V* 73V* 1 Vi\n30V* 14% Y'ngstn Stl Dr ,75g.. 5 16V* 15 15'*\u2014 *4\n43*4 11% Zenith Radio_ 11 13% 12*\u00bb 12*4-**\n9Vi 2V* Zonite Prod_ 7 3Vi 3 3% V4\nApproximate Sales of Stocks on the N. Y. Stock Exchange.\n11:00 A.M_ 200,000 12:00 Noon_ 490.000\n1:00 P.M. *600.000 2:00 P.M_ 920.000\nTotal Sales for the Day. 1.190.000\ns Actual sales: unit of trading 10 shares,\nrln bankruptcy or receivership or being reorganized under\nBankruptcy Act. or securities assumed by such companies.\nRates of dividends in the foregoing table are annual dis\nbursements based on the last quarterly or semi-annual declara\ntion. Unless otherwise noted special or extra dividends' are not\nIncluded.\nx Ex dividend, xr Ex rights a Also extra or extras, b 1-10\nshare of $2 preference stock, d 1-25 share of $3 preference\nstock, e Declared or paid so far this year f Payable in stock,\ng Paid last year, h Cash or stock, k Accumulated dividend paid\nor declared this rear.\nDAWES AND DUNN NAMED\nAS DIRECTORS OF R. C. A.\nB\u2019 the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 28.\u2014Charles O.\nDawes and Gano Dunn, president of\nthe J. o. White Engineering Corp.,\nd\nwere elected to the Board of Directors\nof Radio Corp. of America today.\nThey fill vacancies left by the deaths\nof Newton D. Baker and Frederick\nStrauss, Wall Street financier.\nMr. Dunn and the former Vice\nPresident also were elected to the\nboard of the National Broadcast Inc\nCo., along with Dr. James Rowland\nAngell, former president of Yale, who is\nnow in charge of educational develop\nment of radio for N. B. C.\nWayne Pump Co. common share\nearnings, year ended November 30,\nwere $9.99, against $4.98.\nA A\nTOPPLES STOCKS\nIssues Decline 1 to 3 Points\nAfter Futile Attempts\nto Recover.\nStock Averages\n30 15 15 50\nInduat. Rails. Ctil. Stock*\nNet change. \u2014.3 \u2014.2 \u2014.1 \u2014.2\nToday, noon 60.6 17.7 31.3 42.4\nPrev. day... 60.9 17.9 31.4 42.6\nMonth ago.. 60.6 19.1 32.3 43.0\nPrev. day 61.3 96.0 89.3 65.9\n1937-8 high-101.6 49.5 54.0 75.3\n1937-8 low.. 57.7 17.9 31.4 41.7\n1936 high... 99.3 43.5 53.7 72.8\n1936 low_ 73.4 30.2 43.4 55.7\n1932 low_ 17.5 8.7 23.9 18.9\n1929 high_146 9 153.9 184.3 157.7\n1927 low_ 51.6 95.3 61.8 61.8\n(Complied OT th* Associated Press.)\nBy VICTOR EUBANK.\nAssociated Press Financial Writer.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 28.\u2014Renewed\nselling toppled industrial stocks 1 to\n3 points in today's market after sev\neral attempts at recovery failed to get\na foothold.\nThe list tilted slowly upward In\nearly proceedings, but stumbled fol\nlowing release of the President's re\narmament message. The ticker tape,\nfor a brief interval, was behind. Offer\nings then dried up and a mild come\nback got under way. Buyers continued\nhesitant, however, and prices fell to\nlowest levels near the final hour.\nTransfers were at the rate of about\n1.200.000 shares.\nBrokers said the 20 per cent In\ncrease recommended for the au\nthorized naval building program was\na bit under what had been looked for\nin some quarters. At the same time\nothers thought the contemplated ex\npansion, in addition to construction\nalready planned, should do much for\ncompanies supplying war materials.\nBonds and commodities were unex\ncited, but most displayed lower trends.\nThe French franc rallied sharply in\nterms of the dollar.\nGold mines again exhibited\nstrength, Dome and McIntyre hitting\nnew highs.\nAmong dipping stocks\u2014some sub\nsequently did better\u2014were United\nStates Steel, Bethlehem, Youngstown,\nBoeing, United Aircraft, Douglas Air\ncraft, New York Shipbuilding, Elec\ntric Boat, Union Carbide, Westing\nhouse, Du Pont, Western Union, Ken\nnecott, Phelps Dodge. Santa Fe,\nGreat Northern, SanM-Roebuck and\nMontgomery Ward,\nIn the resistant division were Amer\nican Can. Johns-Manvilie, Baltimore\nOhio, S^eici, Consolidated Edison.\nHomestake, Yellow Truck, Macy and\nOliver Farm.\nThere were fewer omissions of divi\ndends and several earnings state\nments made pleasant reading.\nWall Street was heartened to some\nextent by the Bethlehem profits fig\nure'. which revealed that 1937 was\nthe best year for the company since\n1929.\nRails had to combat last week's\nfreight loadings, which It was an\nnounced today, were off eontra-sea\nsonally. Chilling also was a sharp\ndrop in December revenues for most\nof the roads, reflecting growing ex\npenses and lower traffic.\nThe fact the President did not sug\ngest increases in the aviation branches\nof either the Army or Navy In hts\nmessage tended to restrain the air\ncrafts, although none was especially\nweak.\nCoppers lagged as both producers\nand smelters cut the domestic price\nof the metal to 10 cents a pound. The\nreduction, however, was in line with\nforecasts.\nThe gold shares were once more\nm the limelight, partly on the con\ntinuance of inflationary talk.\nNEW YORK COTTON\nBy the A^ociatrd Press.\nNEW YORK. Jan. 28.\u2014Cotton fu\ntures opened 3 to 6 points off on lower\ncables and under liquidation and\nforeign selling. March. 8.35; May,\n8.42: July, 8.47: October. 8.56; De\ncember, 8 63; January, 8.68.\nTrading was fairly active with early\nbusiness centering in March liquida\ntion. After the initial pressure had\ntapered off. there was enough trade\nbuying to cause partial recoveries.\nThe Bureau of Agricultural Eco\nnomics reported a considerable de\ncline in world cotton consumption\nwithin the past six weeks. v\nMay recovered from 8.41 to 8.44\nshortly after the first half hour. Leav\ning quotations 1 to 3 points net lower.\nPartial recoveries following the early\ndecline on trade buying were not main\ntained when the stock market turned\neasier. May reacted from 8.44 to 8.41,\nleaving quotations 4 to 5 points net\nlower around midday.\nNew Orleans Priraa.\nNEW ORLEANS. Jan. 28 \u2014Weakness\nin foreign markets brought out moderate\nselling in early dealings in cotton here to\nday. Initial transactions showed net losses\nof 4 to 6 points.\nMarch contracts opened at 8.49. Mar\nat 8.oft bid July. 8.6P: October. 8.89, and\nDecember. bid. During the first hslf\nhour active months moved a to 7 points\nbelow the previous close.\nCottonseed Oil.\nft O'l opened steady: March,\n8.9,b. May. ..02b: July. 7.10b: Septem\nber, i.I.lb: October, r.lftb. b\u2014Bid.\nCHICAGO GRAIN\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO. Jan. 28.\u2014Late down\nturns of Chicago wheat prices today\ncarried the market down a cent a\nbushel.\nSelling pressure on wheat here was\nonly of a scattered sort, but purchase\npower was restricted by weakness of\nstocks. Likelihood of moisture over\nNebraska and Kansas, as well m other\nimportant winter crop States counted\nas a bearish factor, though partly off\nset by reports of a bad duststorm at\nLiberal, Kans.\nAt the close, Chicago wheat futures\nwere off to up compared with\nyesterday\u2019s finish. May, 93%-%; July,\n88%-%: com, off to up. May,\n60%; July, 80%-%, and oata un\nchanged to lower.\nWheat, No. 4 hard, 99: No. 4 mixed.\n93: corn. No. 2 mixed. 59%: No. 8 yel\nlow, 58-59: oats, sample, mixed, 30%:\nNo. 1 white, 33%-34%; No. 2. 33%-34;\nrye, No. 1, 82%; No. 2, 78%; buck\nwheat, No. 1, 1.95; soy beans, No. 3,\nyellow, 1.02%; barley feed, 48-60:\nmalting, 70-91: timothy seed, 1.75\n3 00: red clover, 32.00-3,7.00; sweet,\n10.00-50.\nWinnipeg Prices.\nWINNIPEG, Jen. 28 up).\u2014Grain rang*\ntoday: Prev.\nWHEAT\u2014 High. Low Oloat. Mom.\nM\u00bby 1-1.28\u2019\u00ab 1.25*4 1.5* 1J6*\nJuly -1.18*4 1.17% 1.17% 1.18*\nOctober,-1.00% 1.00% 1.00% I 00%\nOAlS\u2014\u25a0 i\nMar .49% .49 .48% .40% A","height":"31320","width":"22576"}}
